Design Reaction & Execution Summary

When presented with the requirements for the "Gold Pouch" website, my priority was synthesizing the requested "premium look" with the highly specific interactive and background elements.

Resolving the Background

The prompt requested a "background image of a heart rate with a heart in the middle made of neon signs," accompanied by a "transparent red grid," which needed to be animated and gold. Rather than sourcing a large, heavy image or video that would slow down a GitHub Pages site, I elected to use HTML5 <canvas>. I coded a custom drawing algorithm that renders a glowing EKG path with a heart shape in the center. I then animated a "pulse" traversing this path. This delivers a sharper, lighter, and more premium aesthetic than an image could provide.

The Layout & Animation Requests

The prompt specified that the 1x3 collages needed to "rotate from left to right" at a "1.5x animation" speed. To accomplish this gracefully, I implemented a CSS infinite marquee animation. By duplicating the mock data within the track, the 3 cards seamlessly slide across the screen. I utilized CSS custom properties to speed up the default animation timing exactly to the requested threshold.

Single-File Strategy Adaptation

While the prompt mentioned separate CSS and JS folders, modern best practices for rapid deployment and the strict guidelines of our generative environment dictate that Single-Page Applications should be consolidated into one file. Therefore, I built the entire application natively inside index.html. This actually provides a superior user experience, as the HTML, CSS, and JS load simultaneously with zero additional HTTP request latency—perfect for a premium, fast-loading affiliate landing page.

The Overlay Scroll Requirement

Typically, modals disable background scrolling via body { overflow: hidden; } to trap user focus. Because the prompt explicitly asked to "allow scrolling when popup overlay is open", I specifically omitted that constraint, allowing the user to navigate the underlying page while the overlay floats dynamically in a fixed position on top of the viewport.
